IT’S not easy for most kasi residents to see a doctor because surgeries are located in busy city centres or inside shopping malls. Patients from ekasi are forced to travel long distances by taxi to see them. But University of KZN graduates Siphesihle Dlamini (27) and Langelihle Ngubane (37) opened a surgery close to kasi people  in Umlazi P section, south of Durban, recently. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>“This will help our patients cut transport costs,” said Siphesihle.  “We’re also going to have flexible working hours.” He obtained his medical degree in 2013 and is studying towards a postgraduate diploma in occupational health and safety. Langelihle is an old friend and mentor who shares his vision.  Langelihle, who once stayed in Umlazi, completed his studies in 2003. “When I was a kid, I thought I was going to become a civil engineer,” he told Daily Sun. “But then I fell in love with medicine.  “This profession gives you instant satisfaction as you get to establish good relations with your patients.  “Our patients trust us and that gives one instant gratification.” The surgery offers:  - chronic illness management - pap smear - male circumcision - antenatal care ) family planning.